The following data is coming from ‘ToothGrowth’, a built in dataset in R looking at the tooth growth of guinea pigs in response to Vitamin C.

Here are a few plots showing the tooth growth in Guinea Pigs that received varying doses of Vitamin C from either Orange Juice or Ascorbic acid.

ggplot(ToothGrowth, aes(dose, len, colour = supp)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(colour = "Supplement type", title = "Tooth Growth of Guinea Pigs", y =
         "Tooth Length (mm?)", x = 
         "Vitamin C dose in mg/day")

ggplot(ToothGrowth, aes(dose, len, colour = supp)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth() +
  labs(fill = "Supplement type", title = "Tooth Growth of Guinea Pigs", y =
         "Tooth Length (mm?)", x = 
         "Vitamin C dose in mg/day")

Here’s a really ugly graph.

ggplot(ToothGrowth, aes(dose, len, fill = supp)) +
  geom_polygon()

Now we can look at some models of our Tooth growth data.

model_2 <- lm(len ~ supp, data = ToothGrowth)
anova(model_2)
model_1 <- lm(len ~ dose, data = ToothGrowth)
anova(model_1)

Guinea Pig tooth lengths range from 4.2 to 33.9

summary1 <- summarise(group_by(ToothGrowth, dose),
                      n = n(),
                      mean = mean(len),
                      sd = sd(len))
